Pantheriae Soulmender 48 Vah Shir Warrior<BR></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/udiae.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Diae</A> at: 3/6/02 11:11:04 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=raspenex>Raspenex</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/6/02 11:40:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1493.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The very most common dual-comp'ing that I've seen ..</span><hr size=1> Like the above poster, I also play 3 accounts at once. SK/cleric/enchanter. While warrior/cleric is a good combination, the addition of the enchanter for crowd control allows entry to places that two could not go.<br>
<br>
Of course, playing 3 at once is nowhere near as efficient as having 3 separate people in control. There are places I will not go as a trio, because it becomes too difficult as you get swarmed. I'd never go to the Planes, for example, as a trio.<br>
<br>
Navigating in dungeons is the worst part, as auto-follow generally doesn't work. I generally don't go to places like LGuk or SolB with just my 3, as it's just too easy to get overrun.<br>
<br>
The advantages of dual or even triple accounts are well worth the difficulties of control, in my opinion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/useenyor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Seenyor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/6/02 3:03:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1493.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The very most common dual-comp'ing that I've seen ..</span><hr size=1> /ooc I have a 43 Ranger, my wife has a 43 Druid.  There are times when she doesn't wanna play so I play both.  I've found that quad kiting can be fairly easy to do if I have the ranger auto-follow.  The ranger has a pathetic AoE (Invoke Lightning) so he is able to quad with the druid.  The spell isnt too effective, but it adds about 25dmg extra to each .  I round up with the druid, on the last pass have the ranger follow.  I cast first with the ranger, then the druid.  Rinse, repeat till they are dead.  If that last pesky one is still following, root, let the ranger melee it to death.  <br>
<br>
Animal fear killing is also pretty easy as well. (The ones that scowl)<br>
<br>
I've found this to be a very effective combo.<br>
<br>
My 2cp for what its worth..<br>
